ABOUT

The Pitch

I’m a meticulous and detail-driven web-QA-tester-turned-UX-Designer with a background in photography, customer service, and support. Testing has given me an immense appreciation for the user research aspect of UX and a desire to help prevent usability issues early in the project lifecycle. To the table, I bring the 25 years of expert Photoshop experience I’ve somehow managed to slip under my belt through both creative and web design. Well, one thing led to another and — TA-DAH! — my intermediate web development skills were born! And, because efficiency is important to me, “streamlining and optimising processes” has played a big role in the work I’ve done over the years.

My time in customer service and managing support put me on the frontline of the user experience and has made me more empathetic towards the humans on the receiving end of products and services.

From a young age, I’ve always wanted to help make life easier for people. Now, with an employer who knows what it means to make a difference in the world, I can put my extensive UX skill set to use doing just that!

Why BabyThunderball?!

Back in the day, CB radios and custom vans were all the rage and my dad had both! When I was five years old and living in Ft. Worth, Texas, he had this van that was an amazing mix of fiery rusty oranges that looked like flames to me, and it had a fridge with a working sink and a sofa bed in the back. It was awesome! We took a lot of cross-country road trips in that thing.

In this beast, my dad had installed a CB radio. Now, if you know anything about CBs, you know there’s a lot of slang involved and that anyone who uses one needs to have a “handle”, a moniker with which to identify yourself on the airwaves. Well, in 1965 (about eight years before I was born), "Thunderball", the fourth instalment of the James Bond franchise which starred hot throb Sean Connery, made its debut. It was one of my dad’s favourite movies at the time, so he chose its title as his handle.

Whenever we went out in the van, my dad would get on the CB and start jawboning with the Chain Gang, other fellow CB-ers and truckers out there sharing the road with us, and making it a better, less lonely place for those whose job it was to haul goods long distances. He’d say cool stuff like, “Breaker breaker 1-9, this is Thunderball comin’ atcha from I-30 over in Cowtown. Just passed a lame portable parking lot at marker two-five-oh.” and “We got a Kojak with a Kodak hidin’ in the grass over here on I-20 at marker one-two-five. Y’all peel your eyeballs if you’re headed that way.” I loved hearing him talk on the CB! It was the Coolest. Thing. Ever.

Well, one day he let li'l ol’ me get on the mic and do a little jawboning of my own! Of course, I had to have a handle to identify myself, so being a chip off the ol’ block, “Baby Thunderball” was born! It was so much fun knowing that I was talking to people I’d never met before from all over the place who happened to be passing through my town for one reason or another.

I’ll never forget how proud I was and how cool it felt to talk to the “big kids” as my daddy’s sidekick. We were the dynamic duo — Thunderball and Baby Thunderball — and people got such a kick out of hearing me talk the talk at the tender age of five. It was nice to hear the smiles in their voices and to know I was making the world a better place in some small way!

Keep your eyes-n-ears open & your black stack a-smokin’!
